<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1437,151,487]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,320,306,332]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Remarks:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[327,549,306,331]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Hemipenthes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curta">
<emphasis box="[327,549,306,331]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Hemipenthes curta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is related to 
<emphasis box="[698,1001,306,331]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<taxonomicName box="[698,814,306,331]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Hemipenthes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="celeris">H. celeris</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[825,1001,306,331]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Hemipenthes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="martinorum">H. martinorum</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
, and 
<taxonomicName box="[1063,1203,306,331]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Hemipenthes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pleuralis">
<emphasis box="[1063,1203,306,331]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">H. pleuralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, as all these species have the same genital structure and similar wing pigmentation, with a smooth color margin, not sinuous as in the other species in the genus. 
<taxonomicName box="[507,729,384,409]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Hemipenthes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curta">
<emphasis box="[507,729,384,409]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Hemipenthes curta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is separated from these species by the lack of color in cell 
<emphasis box="[1414,1429,384,409]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">a</emphasis>
. This species is distributed in the Nearctic and Neotropical regions, with its most northern limit in California, Arizona, New 
<collectingCountry box="[323,412,461,487]" name="Mexico" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Mexico</collectingCountry>
and Texas.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
